		<img width="2501" height="1200" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-aquaculture-cleanup.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-aquaculture-cleanup.jpg 2501w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-aquaculture-cleanup-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-aquaculture-cleanup-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-aquaculture-cleanup-768x368.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-aquaculture-cleanup-1536x737.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-aquaculture-cleanup-2048x983.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-aquaculture-cleanup-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2501px) 100vw, 2501px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">In open-net-pen aquaculture, marine life is raised in nets suspended in the ocean. It involves a lot of equipment that needs to be removed when the work is done. Photo by Deep Search Diving</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">The Destructive Legacy of Failed Aquaculture</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">Removing abandoned infrastructure is challenging, time-consuming, and costly.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/larry-pynn/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Larry Pynn</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						December 6, 2024 | 1,000 words, about 5 minutes
					</aside>

					
				</header>

				
